ith leaves like those of ivy, but %0asofter, and not so long in the stalk, and the seed of it is %0apointed and downy, with a division running down it, and a %0avery powerful smell. Given in their food with water, the seed %0ais poisonous 41 to dogs and all other quadrupeds. %0a%0aCHAP. 59 .- EOSEMAHY : EIGHTEEN KEMEDIES. %0a%0aThere are two kinds of rosemary ; one of which is barren, %0aand the other has a stem with a resinous seed, known as %0a“ cachrys.” The leaves have the odour of frankincense . 43 %0aThe root, applied fresh, effects the cure of wounds, prolapsus %0aof the rectum, condylomata, and piles. The juice of the %0aplant, as well as of the root, is curative of jaundice, and such %0adiseases as require detergents ; it is useful also for the sight. %0aThe seed is given in drink for inveterate diseases of the chest, %0aand, with wine and pepper, for affections of the uterus; it %0aacts also as an emmenagogue, and is used with meal of darnel %0aas a liniment for gout. It acts also as a detergent upon %0afreckles, and is used as an application in diseases which %0arequire calorifics or sudorifics, and for convulsions. The plant %0aitself, or else the root, taken in wine, increases the milk, and %0athe leaves and stem of the plant are applied with vinegar %0ato scrofulous sores; used with honey, they are very useful for %0acough. %0a%0a33 “ Aureum poculum.” %0a%0a40 Desfontaines says that it is the Periploca angustifolia; Fee gives the %0aApocynum folio subrotundo of C. Bauhin, round leafed do°-sbane. %0a%0a11 This is the fact; and hence one of its names “ cynanche,” or “ dog- %0astrangle.” %0a%0athis, Fee says, is the fact. The plant is rich in essential oil, and is %0aconsequently a powerful excitant. See B. xix. c. 62. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 62.] %0a%0a%0aSELAOO. %0a%0a%0a41 %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 60 . -THE SEED CALLED CACHETS. %0a%0aAs already 43 stated, there are several kinds of cachrys ; 44 %0abut that which is produced by rosemary above-mentioned, %0awhen rubbed,