xpresses himself at a loss to decide. %0a%0a77 Probably the Iledysarum onobrychis of Linnaeus, our sainfoin. %0a%0a78 They are very much larger than those of the lentil, in fact. This %0adiversity has caused Fee to express some doubts whether it really is iden¬ %0atical with sainfoin. The Polygala officinalis has also been suggested. %0a%0a79 Dalechauips considers these appellations to mean the “ vir%3cnns’ plant,” %0aand the “plant of beauty.” %0a%0a80 The Cissampelos Pareira, as already stated, abounds in mucilage to %0asuch a degree, as to impart a consistency to water, without impairing its %0atransparency. See c. 72 of this Book. %0a%0a%0aChap. 101.] %0a%0a%0aTHE APROXIS. %0a%0a%0a63 %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 100. —THE M1NSAS OB CORINTHIA: ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aPythagoras gives the name of minsas 81 too, or corinthia, to %0aanother plant; a decoction of which, used as a fomentation, %0awill effect an instantaneous cure of stings inflicted by serpents, %0aaccording to him. He adds too, that if this decoction is poured %0aupon the grass, and a person happens to tread upon it, or if %0athe body should chance to be sprinkled with it, the result is %0afatal beyond all remedy; so monstrously malignant are the %0avenomous proporties of this plant, except as neutralizing %0aother kinds of poison. %0a%0aCHAP 101. -THE APROXIS: SIX REMEDIES. %0a%0aPythagoras makes mention, too, of a plant called aproxis, %0athe root of which takes fire 82 at a distance, like naphtha, of %0awhich we have made some mention, when speaking 83 of the mar¬ %0avellous productions of the earth. He says too, that if the %0ahuman body happens to be attacked by any disease while the %0acabbage 81 is in blossom, the person, although he may have %0abeen perfectly cured, will be sensible of a recurrence of the %0asymptoms, every time that plant comes into blossom; a %0apeculiarity which he attributes to it in common with wheat, %0ahemlock, and the violet. %0a%0aI am not ignorant, however, that the work of his from %