ine: %0athose among them, however, which refuse to take it will be sure %0ato die of that disease. Some persons too are of opinion that %0aif slips of it are put into a bird’s nest, they will effectually %0aprevent the young birds from choking themselves by eating too %0avoraciously. %0a%0aCHAP. 114.—THE PLANT CALLED VENUS* COMB: ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aFrom its resemblance to a comb, they give the name of %0a“ Venus’ comb” 29 to a certain plant, the root of which, bruised %0a%0aK Fee suggests that this may possibly be tbe Spiraea ulmaria of Linnam %0a%0a27 The “ impious ” or “ unnatural ” plant. Fee identifies it with the %0aFilago Gallica of Linnaeus, the corn cudweed. It is destitute of medicinal %0aproperties, and what Pliny states is without foundation. %0a%0a29 Generally identified with the Scandix pecten Veneris, corn cicely, or %0ashepherd’s needle. See B. xxii. c. 38. %0a%0a%0aChap. 117.] %0a%0a%0aTO HD ST LON Oil SYREON. %0a%0a%0an %0a%0a%0awith mallows, extracts all foreign substances from the human %0a%0abody. %0a%0ar %0a%0aCHAP. 115.-THE EXEDUM. THE PLANT CALLED NOTIA : TWO %0a%0aKEMEDIES. %0a%0aThe plant called “ exedum” 30 is curative of lethargy. The %0aherbaceous plant called “notia,” which is used by curriers %0afor dyeing leather a bright, cheerful colour, and known by %0athem under various names—is curative of cancerous ulcers; %0aI find it also stated that, taken in wine or in oxycrate, it is %0aextremely efficacious for stings inflicted by scorpions. %0a%0aCHAr. 116.-THE rniLANTUROPOS : ONE REMEDY. TUE LAPPA %0a%0aCANARIA: TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe Greeks wittily give the name of “ philanthropes” 31 to a %0acertain plant, because it attaches itself to articles of dress. 33 %0aA chaplet made of this plant has the effect of relieving head¬ %0aache. %0a%0aAs to the plant known as the “lappa canaria,” 33 beaten up %0ain wine with plantago and millefolium, 34 it effects the cure of %0acarcinomatous sores, the application being removed at the end of %0athree days. Taken out of the ground without the aid of iron, %0aand thrown into their wash, or given to them in wine and milk, it %0acures diseases in swine. Some persons add, however, that the %0aperson, as he takes it up, must say—“ This is the plant arge- %0ainon, a remedy discovered by Minerva for such swine as shall %0ataste thereof.” %0a%0aCHAP. 117.-TORDYLON OR SYltEON : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aTordylon is, according to some authorities, the seed of sili, 36 %0awhile according to others it is a distinct plant, 36 known also %0aas “syrcon.” I find no particulars relative to it, except that %0a%0aM Fee queries whether this may not possibly be the Rhus coriaria of %0aLinnaeus, elm-leaved sumach, mentioned in B. xiii. c. 13. He would %0aappear, however, to have confounded it with the Notia, next mentioned. %0a%0a31 “ Man-loving,” or rather “ attached to man.” Identified with the %0aGalium aparine of Linnaeus, goose-grass, or common ladies bedstraw; the %0aseeds of which attach themselves to the dress. 33 See B. xxi. c. 64. %0a%0a33 The dog-bur. The Lappa tomentosa of Lamarck. See B. xxvi. c. 65. %0a%0a34 See c. 95 of this Book. %0a%0a^ Or hartwort; see B. xx. cc. 18, 87. %0a%0a36 The Tordylium officinale of Linnaeus, officinal hart-wort. %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXIV. %0a%0a%0ait grows upon mountains, and that the ashes of it, taken in %0adrink, act as an eiumenagogue and facilitate expectoration. It %0ais stated also, that for this last purpose the root is even more %0aefficacious than the stem ; that the juice of it, taken in doses of %0athree oboli, cures diseases of the kidneys ; and that the root is %0aused as an ingredient for emollient plasters. %0a%0aCHAP. 118. -GUAMKN : SEVENTEEN REMEDIES. %0a%0aGramen 37 is of all herbaceous productions the most common. %0aAs it creeps along the ground it throws out jointed stems, from %0athe joints of which, as well as from the extremity of the stem, %0afresh roots are put forth every here and there. I