ial oil; %0a%3c but no use is made of them in modern medicine. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 20.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE CHAM.EPITXS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 13 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c tions for gatherings ; and a decoction of them is strengthening %0a%3c to the stomach. The seed of it is taken in -wine for head-ache %0a%3c and strangury : it is slightly laxative to the bowels, and acts %0a%3c as an aphrodisiac. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 19 .- THE PITCH-TREE AND THE LARCH: EIGHT REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The leaves of the pitch-tree 75 and the larch , 76 beaten up %0a%3c and boiled in vinegar, are good for tooth-ache. The ashes of %0a%3c the bark are used for excoriations and burns. Taken in drink %0a%3c this substance arrests diarrhoea, and acts as a diuretic; and %0a%3c used as a fumigation, it reduces the uterus when displaced. %0a%3c The leaves of the pitch-tree are particularly good for the liver, %0a%3c taken in doses of one drachma in hydromel. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is a well-known fact that forests planted solely with trees %0a%3c from which pitch and resin are extracted, are remarkably %0a%3c beneficial for patients suffering from phthisis , 77 or who are un¬ %0a%3c able to recover their strength after a long illness: indeed it is %0a%3c said, that in such cases to breathe the air of localities thus %0a%3c planted, is more beneficial even than to take a voyage to Egypt , 78 %0a%3c or to go on a summer’s journey to the mountains to drink the %0a%3c milk there, impregnated with the perfumes of plants. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 20. -THE CHAMJSPITTS : TEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The chamoepitys , 79 called in Latin “ abiga ,” 80 because it %0a%3c promotes abortion, and known to some as “ incense of the %0a%3c earth ,” 81 has branches a cubit in length, and the odour and %0a%3c %0a%3c 75 See B. xvi. c. 18. %0a%3c %0a%3c 76 See B, xvi. c. 19. The leaves of these trees are of an astringent %0a%3c and acid nature, Fee says, but they are no longer employed in medicine. %0a%3c All that Pliny 