ith wine, for pains %0a%3c in the sides: they are employed also lor drawing off the %0a%3c water in dropsy. They have the property, too, of diminish¬ %0a%3c ing obesity, and of gradually reducing the body to a state of %0a%3c comparative emaciation, 31 the follicules being pounded in %0a%3c wine and administered in proportion to the bodily strength; %0a%3c thus, for instance, to a child, live of them are given in three %0a%3c cyathi of wine, but for persons in more robust health, seven %0a%3c are prescribed, in live cyathi of wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c We must not omit to state that the shavings and saw-dust %0a%3c of this wood are of a highly dangerous nature, according to %0a%3c some. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 31 . —THE MAPLE : ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c The root of the maple, 35 beaten up in wine, is extremely %0a%3c efficacious as a topical application for pains in the liver. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 32 . -THE POPLAR : EIGHT REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Wc have already 36 mentioned, when speaking of the un¬ %0a%3c guents, the use that is made of the berries 37 of the white %0a%3c poplar. A potion prepared from the bark is good for sciatica %0a%3c %0a%3c 52 The young leaves probably, or else the fruit. %0a%3c %0a%3c 3.'i j n b. xvi. c. 24. There are still some traces of this notion existing, %0a%3c F£e says, among the French peasantry. All the statements here made re- %0a%3c lative to its medicinal properties, are utterly unfounded. %0a%3c %0a%3c w In reality they have no such effect. %0a%3c %0a%3c 36 See B. xvi. c. 26. The root of the maple, Fee says, has no marked %0a%3c %0a%3c qualities whatever. . %0a%3c %0a%3c 38 In B. xii. c. 61. The buds of the poplar, lee says, are stul usedin %0a%3c medicine in the composition of an unguent known as “populeum. Hie %0a%3c bark is astringent, and the wood destitute of taste. %0a%3c %0a%3c 31 “ Uvarum.” Fee thinks that by these berries, or grapes, the blossoms %0a%3c or buds are meant. See Note 91 to B. xii. c. 61 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 22 PLINY’S N