ly %0a%3c %0a%3c in vogue for the cure of dropsy. ’ %0a%3c %0a%3c 53 This so-called cedar, Fee says, isin reality itself a juniper. The medici¬ %0a%3c nal properties of all the varieties of the juniper are not identical. Theessen- %0a%3c tial oil of the leaves acts with a formidable energy upon the human system. %0a%3c %0a%3c ^ This is identified by Fee with the Juniperus communis of Lamarck, %0a%3c variety a, the Juniperus communis of Linnmus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 55 Identified by Fee with the Juniperus nana of Willdenow the Juni¬ %0a%3c perus communis of Lamarck, variety /3. The Spauish juniper, mentioned %0a%3c in B. xvi. c. 1 6, he identifies with the Juniperus thurifera of Linmeus %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 37.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE WILLOW. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 25 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c proach of serpents. 56 The seed 57 is good for pains in the %0a%3c stomach, chest, and sides; it dispels flatulency and sudden %0a%3c chills, soothes cough, and brings indurations to a head. Ap¬ %0a%3c plied topically, it checks the growth of tumours ; and the %0a%3c berries, taken in red wine, act astringently upon the bowels : %0a%3c they are applied also to tumours of the abdomen. The seed %0a%3c is used as an ingredient in antidotes of an aperient nature, and %0a%3c is diuretic 58 in its effects. It is used as a liniment for de¬ %0a%3c fluxions of the eyes, and is prescribed for convulsions, rup¬ %0a%3c tures, griping pains in the bowels, affections of the uterus, %0a%3c and sciatica, either in a dose of four berries in white wine, or %0a%3c in the form of a decoction of twenty berries in wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c There are persons who rub the body with juniper berries as %0a%3c a preventive of the attacks of serpents. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 37. (9.) -THE WILLOW : FOURTEEN REMEDIES. THF. %0a%3c %0a%3c WILLOW OF AMERIA: ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c The fruit of the willow, 59 before it arrives at maturity, is %0a%3c covered with a down like a spider’s web : gathered 60 before it %0a%3c is ripe, it arrests discharges of blood from the mouth. The %0a%3c bark of the upper branches, reduced to ashes and mixed with %0a%3c water, is curative of corns and callosities: it removes spots %0a%3c also upon the face, being still more efficacious for that purpose %0a%3c if mixed with the juices of the. tree. %0a%3c %0a%3c The juices produced by the willow form three different %0a%3c varieties ; one 61 of which exudes in the shape of a gum from %0a%3c %0a%3c 46 Virgil says this of the fumes of the cedar, Georg. III. 414; an %0a%3c additional proof, Fee says, that under the name of “ cedrus,” the juniper %0a%3c was really meant. The smoke of the juniper is not known to have the %0a%3c effect upon serpents here described. %0a%3c %0a%3c 57 The berries of the juniper contain sugar, mucilage, and a small pro¬ %0a%3c portion of essential oil; a rob is prepared from them, Fee says, under the %0a%3c name of “extract of juniper.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 58 It is a well-known fact, that juniper berries are diuretic ; they impart %0a%3c also to the urine the odour of the violet, a property which is equally pos¬ %0a%3c sessed by turpentine. All the other properties here attributed to the %0a%3c juniper, are, in F£e’s opinion, either hypothetical or absurd. %0a%3c %0a%3c 59 See B. xvi. c. 68. %0a%3c %0a%3c 60 Neither this downy substance nor the seeds are now employed for %0a%3c any purpose. The bark of the willow has some strongly-pronounced pro¬ %0a%3c perties, but all other parts of it are totally inert. %0a%3c %0a%3c 61 A kind of manna, Fee says. The other juices here mentioned are %0a%3c secreted from the sap. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 26 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Flint’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXIV. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c the tree itself, and another distils from an incision some three %0a%3c fingers in width, made in the bark while the tree is in blossom. %0a%3c This last is very useful for dispersing humours which impede %0a%3c the sight, acting also as an inspissative when