aeus, the tree of chastity. %0a%3c %0a%3c 65 The “chaste” tree. It is no longer used in medicine; the fruit has some¬ %0a%3c what the flavour of spice, Fee says, and taken internally it would have the %0a%3c converse of an antaphrodisiac effect. The other parts of it are quite inert. %0a%3c %0a%3c 66 An Attic festival celebrated yearly in honour of Demeter, which %0a%3c lasted four or five days. It was also celebrated in other parts of Greece. %0a%3c %0a%3c 67 The Vitex agnus castus of Lamarck, variety /3, Elatior. %0a%3c %0a%3c 68 The Vitex agnus castus of Linnaeus, the type. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 38.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE VITEX. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 7 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c white blossom mixed with purple, whereas the black one has a %0a%3c flower that is entirely purple. Both of these trees grow on %0a%3c level spots of a marshy nature. %0a%3c %0a%3c The seed of these trees, taken in drink, has a sort of vinous %0a%3c flavour, and has the reputation of being a febrifuge. It is %0a%3c said also to act as a sudorific, if the body is rubbed with it %0a%3c mixed with oil, and to have the effect of dispelling extreme %0a%3c lassitude : it acts too as a diuretic 69 and emmenagogue. The %0a%3c produce of both trees is trying to the head, like wine, and %0a%3c indeed the odour of them is very similar. They have the %0a%3c effect also of removing flatulence in the lower regions of the %0a%3c body, act astringently upon the bowels, and are remarkably %0a%3c useful for dropsy and affections of the spleen. They promote %0a%3c the secretion of the milk, and neutralize the venom of serpents, %0a%3c when of a cold nature more particularly. The smaller kind, %0a%3c however, is the more efficacious of the two for injuries inflicted %0a%3c by serpents, the seed being taken in doses of one drachma, in %0a%3c wine or oxycrate, or else the more tender leaves in doses of two %0a%3c drachmae. %0a%3c %0a%3c From both trees also a liniment is prepared for the bites of %0a%3c spiders, but it is quite sufficient to rub the wounds with the %0a%3c leaves; and if a fumigation is made from them, or if they are %0a%3c spread beneath the bed, they will repel the attacks of all %0a%3c venomous creatures. They act also as an antaphrodisiac, and %0a%3c it is by this tendency in particular that they neutralize the %0a%3c venom of the phalangium, the bite of which has an exciting %0a%3c effect upon the generative organs. The blossoms and young %0a%3c shoots, mixed with oil of roses, allay head-aches arising from %0a%3c inebriation. A decoction of the seed used as a fomentation %0a%3c cures head-ache, however intense it may be ; and employed as %0a%3c a fumigation or as a pessary, the seeds acts as a detergent %0a%3c upon the uterus. Taken in drink with honey and penny-royal, %0a%3c it has a laxative effect; pounded and used with barley-meal, %0a%3c it quickly brings abscesses and hard tumours to a head, and %0a%3c has an emollient effect. %0a%3c %0a%3c The seed, in combination with saltpetre and vinegar, removes %0a%3c lichens and freckles; mixed with honey, it heals ulcers and %0a%3c eruptions of the mouth ; applied with butter and vine-leaves, %0a%3c it reduces swellings of the testes ; used with water, as a lini- %0a%3c %0a%3c 69 It may possibly, Fee says, have tbis effect, but the other properties %0a%3c here attributed to it are wholly imaginary. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 28 pliny’s natural htstory. [Book XXIV. %0a%3c %0a%3c ment, it cures chaps of the rectum; and employed with salt, %0a%3c nitre, and wax, it is good for sprains. The seed and leaves %0a%3c are used as ingredients also in emollient plasters for diseases %0a%3c of the sinews, and for gout; and a decoction ol the seed in oil is %0a%3c employed as a fomentation for the head in cases of phrenitis %0a%3c and lethargy. Persons 70 who carry a sprig of this plant in the %0a%3c hand, or stuck in the girdle, will be proof, it is said, against %0a%3c chafing between the thighs. %0a%3c %0a%3c chap. 39.—the erica; one remedy. %0a%3c %0a%3c The Greeks give the name of “ erice,”' 1 to a shrub that is but %0a%3c little different from the myrice. 73 It has the colour, and very %0a%3c nearly the leaf, of rosemary. It neutralizes 73 the venom of %0a%3c serpents, it is said. %0a%3c %0a%3c chap. 40. —the broom; five remedies. %0a%3c %0a%3c The broom is used for making withes ; 74 the flowers of it %0a%3c are greatly sought by bees. I have my doubts whether this %0a%3c is not the same plant that the Greek writers have called %0a%3c “sparton,” and of which, in those parts of the world, as I have %0a%3c already 15 stated, they are in the habit of making fishing-nets. %0a%3c I doubt also whether Homer 70 has alluded to this plant, when %0a%3c he speaks of the seams of the ships,—“ the sparta” coming %0a%3c asunder; for it is certain that in those times the spartum 77 of %0a%3c Spain or Africa was not as yet in use, and that vessels made %0a%3c of materials sown together, were united by the agency, not of %0a%3c spartum, but of flax. %0a%3c %0a%3c 70 Travelling on horseback, probably. A similar superstition is mentioned %0a%3c as to the poplar, in c. 32 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 71 Probably the Erica arborea of Linnaeus ; see B. xiii. c. 35. It has %0a%3c not, however, a leaf similar to that of rosemary, with the sole exception, %0a%3c Fee says, of the Erica cinerea of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 72 See B. xiii. c. 37. 73 It has no such effect, in reality. %0a%3c %0a%3c 74 See B. xvi. c. 69. The kind here alluded to is the Spanish broom, %0a%3c %0a%3c Fee thinks. 75 In B. xix. c. 2. Vol. 1Y. p. 135. %0a%3c %0a%3c 76 Iliad, B. ii. 1. 135. See B. xix. c. 6, where Pliny states it as his %0a%3c %0a%3c opinion that in this passage Homer is speaking of flax. %0a%3c %0a%3c 77 See B. xix. c. 7. Fee thinks that the plant under consideration in %0a%3c this Chapter is the Spanish broom, Genista juncea of Lamarck, the Spar- %0a%3c tium junceum of Linnaeus, a different plant from the Spart