and all pains iu the sides. %0a%3c %0a%3c The apocynum 40 is a shrub with leaves like those of ivy, but %0a%3c softer, and not so long in the stalk, and the seed of it is %0a%3c pointed and downy, with a division running down it, and a %0a%3c very powerful smell. Given in their food with water, the seed %0a%3c is poisonous 41 to dogs and all other quadrupeds. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 59 .- EOSEMAHY : EIGHTEEN KEMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c There are two kinds of rosemary ; one of which is barren, %0a%3c and the other has a stem with a resinous seed, known as %0a%3c “ cachrys.” The leaves have the odour of frankincense . 43 %0a%3c The root, applied fresh, effects the cure of wounds, prolapsus %0a%3c of the rectum, condylomata, and piles. The juice of the %0a%3c plant, as well as of the root, is curative of jaundice, and such %0a%3c diseases as require detergents ; it is useful also for the sight. %0a%3c The seed is given in drink for inveterate diseases of the chest, %0a%3c and, with wine and pepper, for affections of the uterus; it %0a%3c acts also as an emmenagogue, and is used with meal of darnel %0a%3c as a liniment for gout. It acts also as a detergent upon %0a%3c freckles, and is used as an application in diseases which %0a%3c require calorifics or sudorifics, and for convulsions. The plant %0a%3c itself, or else the root, taken in wine, increases the milk, and %0a%3c the leaves and stem of the plant are applied with vinegar %0a%3c to scrofulous sores; used with honey, they are very useful for %0a%3c cough. %0a%3c %0a%3c 33 “ Aureum poculum.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 40 Desfontaines says that it is the Periploca angustifolia; Fee gives the %0a%3c Apocynum folio subrotundo of C. Bauhin, round leafed do°-sbane. %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 This is the fact; and hence one of its names “ cynanche,” or “ dog- %0a%3c strangle.” %0a%3c %0a%3c this, Fee says, is the fact. The plant is rich in essential oil, and is %0a%3c consequently a powerful excitant. See B. xix. c. 62. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 62.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c SELAOO. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 41 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 60 . -THE SEED CALLED CACHETS. %0a%3c %0a%3c As already 43 stated, there are several kinds of cachrys ; 44 %0a%3c but that which is produced by rosemary above-mentioned, %0a%3c when rubbed, is found to be of a resinous nature. It neu¬ %0a%3c tralizes poisons and the venom of animals, that of serpents %0a%3c excepted. It acts also as a sudorific, dispels griping pains in %0a%3c the bowels, and increases the milk in nursing women. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 61 . -THE HERB SAVIN : SEVEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Of the herb savin, known as “ brathy” by the Greeks , 46 there %0a%3c are two varieties, one of them 48 with a leaf like that of the %0a%3c tamarix, the other 47 with that of the cypress ; for which reason %0a%3c some persons have called this last the Cretan cypress. It is %0a%3c used by many for fumigations, as a substitute for frankin¬ %0a%3c cense ; 48 employed in medicine, it is said to have the same effect %0a%3c as cinnamon, if taken in doses twice as large. It reduces %0a%3c gatherings, disperses corrosive sores, acts as a detergent upon %0a%3c ulcers, and, used as a pessary and as a fumigation, brings away %0a%3c the dead foetus . 49 It is employed as a topical application for %0a%3c erysipelas and carbuncles, and, taken with honey in wine, is %0a%3c curative of jaundice. %0a%3c %0a%3c The smoke of this plant, they say, cures the pip in all kinds %0a%3c of poultry . 60 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 62 . -SELAGO : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Similar to savin is the herb known as “ selago .” 61 Care is %0a%3c %0a%3c 43 In B. xvi. c. 11. %0a%3c %0a%3c 44 A gall or fungoid production, or, in some instances, a catkin. Fee %0a%3c says that Pliny has committed an error here in attributing a cachrys to %0a%3c rosemary, the Libauotis stephanomaticos, which, in reality, belongs to %0a%3c the Libanotis canchryphorus or Libanotis prima. %0a%3c %0a%3c 45 So called from the Greek fipaSv, “ slow,” according to some au¬ %0a%3c thorities; by reason of the slowness of its growth. %0a%3c %0a%3c 46 Identified by Fee with the Sabina vulgatior of Lobelius, or Juniperus %0a%3c Sabina, variety /3, of Lamarck. %0a%3c %0a%3c 47 The Sabina baceifera of J. Bauhin, the male savin, the type of the %0a%3c plant. %0a%3c %0a%3c 48 See Ovid’s Fasti, B. i. 1. 341, as to this custom, and Virgil’s “ Culex,” %0a%3c 1. 403. %0a%3c %0a%3c 49 It is still a common notion, though Fee says an ill-founded one, that %0a%3c it produces abortion. Indeed we find Galen stating to the same effect. %0a%3c %0a%3c 30 Fee ridicules this notion with considerable zest. %0a%3c %0a%3c 41 Tho Lycopodium sclago of Linnaeus, upright club-moss, or fir- moss, %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 42 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c flint's natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXIV. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c taken to gather it without the use of iron, the right hand %0a%3c being passed for the purpose through the left sleeve of the %0a%3c tunic, as though the gatherer were in the act of committing a %0a%3c theft . 52 The clothing too must be white, the feet bare and %0a%3c washed clean, and a sacrifice of bread and wine must be made %0a%3c before gathering it: it is carried also in a new napkin. The %0a%3c Druids of Gaul have pretended that this plant should be %0a%3c carried about the person as a preservative against accidents of %0a%3c all kinds, and that the smoke of it is extremely good for all %0a%3c maladies of the eyes. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 63 .- SAMOLUS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The Druids, also, have given the name of “ samolus ’ to a %0a%3c certain plant which grows in humid localities. This too, they %0a%3c say, must be gathered fasting with the left hand, as a pre¬ %0a%3c servative against the maladies to which swine and cattle are %0a%3c soibject. The person, too, who gathers it must be careful not %0a%3c to look behind him, nor must it be laid anywhere but in the %0a%3c troughs from which the cattle drink. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 64.—GUM : ELEVEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c We have already 51 spoken of the different kinds of gum; %0a%3c the better sort of each kind will be found the most effective. %0a%3c Gum is bad for the teeth; it tends to make the blood coagu¬ %0a%3c late, and is consequently good for discharges 55 of blood from %0a%3c the mouth. It is useful for burns , 56 but is bad for diseases of %0a%3c the trachea. It exercises a diuretic effect, and tends to %0a%3c neutralize all acridities, being astringent in other respects. %0a%3c The gum of the bitter-almond tree, which, has the most 57 %0a%3c %0a%3c according to Sprengel. Fee, however, dissents from that opinion, for the %0a%3c Lycopodium, he says, is but some three inches in height, while savin, with %0a%3c which the Selago is here compared, is more than eight or ten feet high. De %0a%3c Theis {Gloss. Botan.) thinks that it must have been a succulent plant; but %0a%3c upon what grounds he bases that conjecture, Fee declares himself at a loss %0a%3c to conjecture. %0a%3c %0a%3c 52 Evidently a superstition derived from the Druids. %0a%3c %0a%3c 53 Sprengel thinks that it is the Samolus Valerandi of Linnaeus, the round- %0a%3c leaved water-pimpernel, and Anguillara identifies it with the Anemone pul- %0a%3c satilla, or pasque-flower. Fee inclines to the opinion that it is the Veronica %0a%3c beceabunga of Linnaeus, the brook-lime. %0a%3c %0a%3c 54 In B. xiii. c. 20. %0a%3c %0a%3c 55 Gum is still used, Fee says, for this purpose. %0a%3c %0a%3c 56 It is of no use whatever for burns, or as a diuretic. %0a%3c %0a%3c 57 Fee says that it is not different in any way from the gum of other trees. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c GEM ACACIA. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 43 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 67.] %0a%3c %0a%3c astringent properties of them all, is calorific also in its effects. %0a%3c Still, however, the gum of the plum, cherry, and vine is %0a%3c greatly preferred : all which kinds, applied topically, are pro¬ %0a%3c ductive of astringent and desiccative effects, and, used with %0a%3c vinegar, heal lichens upon infants. Taken in must, in doses %0a%3c of four oboli, they are good for inveterate coughs. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is generally thought that gum, taken in raisin wine, %0a%3c improves the complexion , 58 sharpens the appetite, and is %0a%3c good for calculi 69 in the bladder. It is particularly useful too %0a%3c for wounds and affections of the eyes. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 65 . ( 12 .)- THE EGYPTIAN OR ARABIAN THORN J POUR %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c When speaking 60 of the perfumes, we have descanted upon %0a%3c the merits of the Egyptian or Arabian thorn. This, too, is of %0a%3c an astringent nature, and acts as a desiccative upon fluxes of %0a%3c all kinds, discharges of blood from the mouth, and excessive %0a%3c menstruation; for all which purposes the root is still more %0a%3c efficacious. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 66.-THE WHITE THORN : TWO REMEDIES. THE ACANTHION ; %0a%3c %0a%3c ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c The seed of the white thorn is useful as a remedy for the %0a%3c stings of scorpions, and a chaplet made of it, is good for head¬ %0a%3c ache. Similar to this plant is that known to the Greeks as %0a%3c the “ acanthion ;” 61 though it is much smaller in the leaf, which %0a%3c is pointed at the extremity, and covered with a down like a %0a%3c cobweb in appearance. This downy substance is gathered in %0a%3c the East, and certain textures are made of it similar to those %0a%3c of silk. An infusion of the leaves or root of this plant is taken %0a%3c for the cure of opisthotony. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 67 . -GEM ACACIA : EIGHTEEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Gum acacia is produced also from the white and black 62 %0a%3c %0a%3c 5 " Fee remarks, that gum is injurious as a cosmetic. %0a%3c %0a%3c 59 Gum is of no use whatever in such a case. %0a%3c %0a%3c 60 In B. xiii. c. 19. In speaking there, however, of this gum, the %0a%3c Acacia Nilotica of Linnaeus, he makes no mention whatever of Arabia; %0a%3c