 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 69 . -THE ERYSISCEPTRUM, ADIPSATHEON, OR DJAXYLON : %0a%3c %0a%3c EIGHT REMEDTES. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is also found in the islands of Nisyros and of Rhodes, %0a%3c a shrub of smaller size, but full as thorny, known by some as %0a%3c the erysisceptrum, 72 by others as the adipsatheon, and by the %0a%3c Syrians as the diaxylon. The best kind is that which is the %0a%3c least 73 ferulaceous in the stem, and which is of a red colour, or %0a%3c inclining to purple, when the bark is removed. It is found %0a%3c growing in many places, but is not everywhere odoriferous. %0a%3c We have already 74 stated how remarkably sweet the odour of %0a%3c it is, when the rainbow has been extended over it. %0a%3c %0a%3c This plant cures fetid ulcers of the mouth, polypus 78 of the %0a%3c nose, ulcerations or carbuncles of the generative organs, and %0a%3c chaps ; taken in drink it acts as a carminative, and is curative %0a%3c of strangury. The bark is good for patients troubled with %0a%3c discharges of blood, and a decoction of it acts astringently on %0a%3c the bowels. It is generally thought that the wild plant is %0a%3c productive of the same effects. %0a%3c %0a%3c 69 Fbe suggests that this may be the Dipsacus fullonum of Linnaeus, %0a%3c the fuller’s thistle. %0a%3c %0a%3c %3c u See B. xix. c. 18, and c. 58 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 In B. xii. c. 52. But in that passage he makes the Aspalathos to be %0a%3c identical with the Erysisceptrum, which he here distinguishes from it. Fee %0a%3c thinks that there can be no identity between the common thorn here men¬ %0a%3c tioned, and the Aspalathos. This latter, as mentioned in B. xii., according %0a%3c to Fee, is the Convolvulus scoparius of Linnaeus, the broom bindweed, but %0a%3c Littre says that M. Fraas has identified it with the Genista acanthoclada. %0a%3c %0a%3c 73 See the preceding Note. Fee identifies this Aspalathos with the %0a%3c Spartiura villosum of Linnaeus, making that of B xii. c. 52, to be the Lignum %0a%3c lihodianum of commerce, probably the Convolvulus scoparius of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 73 The corresponding passage in Dioscorides has flapvs, “heavy,” e. %0a%3c the most- solid in the stem. %0a%3c %0a%3c 74 In B. xii. c. 52. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c r * “ Ozsenas.” %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 46 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXIV. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 70 . -THE THORN CALLED APPENDIX : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c THE TYRACANTHA : ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is a thorn also known as the appendix ; that name %0a%3c being given to the red berries which hang from its branches. %0a%3c These berries eaten by themselves, raw, or else dried and %0a%3c boiled in wine, arrest looseness of the bowels and dispel %0a%3c griping pains in the stomach. The berries ol the pyracantha %0a%3c are taken in drink for wounds inflicted by serpents. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 71 .- THE PALIURDS : TEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The paliurus, 78 too, is a kind of thorn. The seed of it, known %0a%3c by the people of Africa as “ zura,” is extremely efficacious for %0a%3c the sting of the scorpion, as also for urinary calculi and cough. %0a%3c The leaves are of an astringent nature, and the root disperses %0a%3c inflamed tumours, gatherings, and abscesses; taken in drink %0a%3c it is diuretic in its effects. A decoction of it in wine arrests %0a%3c diarrhoea, and neutralizes the venom of serpents: the root %0a%3c more particularly is administered in wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 72 . -THE AGRIFOLIA. THE AQUIFOLIA : ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c THE YEW I ONE PROPERTY BELONGING TO IT. %0a%3c %0a%3c The agrifolia, 79 pounded, with the addition of salt, is good %0a%3c for diseases of the joints, and the berries are used in cases of %0a%3c excessive menstruation, coeliac affections, dysentery, and %0a%3c cholera ; taken in wine, they act astringently upon the bowels. %0a%3c A decoction of the root, applied externally, extracts foreign %0a%3c bodies from the flesh, 