ve %0a%3c of alopeey: and the bramble-berries themselves, combined with %0a%3c oil of ompliacium, 4 stain 5 the hair. The blossom of the bram¬ %0a%3c ble is gathered at harvest, and the white blossom, taken in %0a%3c wine, is an excellent remedy for pleurisy and coeliac affections. %0a%3c The root, boiled down to one third, arrests looseness of the %0a%3c bowels and haemorrhage, and a decoction of it, used as a gargle, %0a%3c is good for the teeth : the juice too is employed as a fomenta¬ %0a%3c tion for ulcers of the rectum and generative organs. The %0a%3c ashes of the root are curative of relaxations of the uvula. %0a%3c %0a%3c 36 The fruit, Fee says, of the wild eglantine. See B. xxv. c. 6. %0a%3c %0a%3c 97 Or “ dog-bramble.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 98 “Dog-strangle,” apparently. %0a%3c %0a%3c 99 “ Drawn with a string.” Fee thinks that Pliny has confused the %0a%3c %0a%3c account given of this plant with that of the Aglaophotis, mentioned in %0a%3c c. 102 of this Book, and that the Cynosbatos is only a variety of the Rub us %0a%3c or bramble. Other authorities identify it with the Rubus caninus, or with %0a%3c the Rosa sempervirens. Desfontaines thinks that it is the Ribes nigrum, %0a%3c or black currant; and Littre is of opinion that some gooseberry or currant %0a%3c tree is meant. 1 See B. xiii. c. 44. %0a%3c %0a%3c 2 “Thyrsus.” Fee thinks that the allusion is to the produce of the %0a%3c caper, while Hardouin says that it is the first cynosbatos that he is speak¬ %0a%3c ing of. Hardouin is probably right. %0a%3c %0a%3c 3 The blossom, perhaps, of the Rubus fruticosus, or blackberry. %0a%3c %0a%3c 4 See B. xii. c. 60. %0a%3c %0a%3c 5 Fee says that they have no such property, and that the blossoms of the %0a%3c bramble ate entirely destitute of any known medicinal qualities. The %0a%3c roots and leaves are somewhat astringent. %0a%3c %0a%3c VOL. V. 2 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 50 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXIV. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 75.-THE ID.-EAN BRAMBLE. %0a%3c %0a%3c The Idsean bramble 8 is so called from the fact that it is the %0a%3c only plant of the kind found growing upon Mount Ida. It is %0a%3c of a more delicate nature than the others, and smaller; the %0a%3c canes too are thinner, and not 7 so prickly: it mostly grows %0a%3c beneath the shade of trees. The blossom of it, mixed with %0a%3c honey, is applied topically for defluxions of the eyes, and is %0a%3c administered in water for erysipelas and affections of the %0a%3c stomach. 8 In other respects, it has properties similar to those %0a%3c of the plants 9 already mentioned. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAT. 76 .- THE RHAMNOS; TWO VARIETIES OF IT: FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Among the several kinds 10 of bramble is reckoned the plant %0a%3c called “ rhamnos” by the Greeks. One variety of it is whiter" %0a%3c than the other, and has a more shrublike appearance, throwing %0a%3c out branches armed with straight thorns, and not hooked, like %0a%3c those of the other kinds; the leaves too are larger. The other %0a%3c kind, 12 which is found growing wild, is of a more swarthy hue, %0a%3c in some measure inclining to red ; it bears too a sort 13 of pod. %0a%3c With the root of it boiled in water a medicament is made, %0a%3c known as “lycium:” 14 the seed of it is useful for bringing %0a%3c away the after-birth. The white kind, however, is of a more %0a%3c astringent and cooling nature, and better adapted for the treat¬ %0a%3c ment of gatherings and wounds. The leaves of both kinds, %0a%3c either raw or boiled, are employed topically with oil. %0a%3c %0a%3c 6 The raspberry; see B. xvi. c. 71. %0a%3c %0a%3c 7 There is one variety which is very diminutive, and entirely destitute %0a%3c %0a%3c of thorns, the Rubus Idseus lsevis of C. Bauhin, the Rubus Idaeus non %0a%3c spinosus of J. Bauhin. 8 See B. xvi. c. 71. %0a%3c %0a%3c 9 Of the bramble genus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 10 In reality, as Fee says, there is no botanical affinity between the %0a%3c Rubus, 