e to the ground; it is found growing in dry, rocky, %0a%3c localities. A decoction of it in wine is remarkably useful as a %0a%3c liniment for improving 36 the sight, and for dispersing cataract, %0a%3c cicatrizations, films, and cloudiness of the eyes. Applied in a %0a%3c pledget of linen, as a pessary, it allays pains in the uterus; %0a%3c and used topically 37 it removes warts and excrescences of all %0a%3c kinds. It is very useful also for hardness of breathing. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 84 . -THE CHAMiECISSOS I ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c The chamaecissos 38 has ears like 39 those of wheat, with %0a%3c numerous leaves, and small branches, about five in number. %0a%3c When in blossom it might almost be taken for the white violet: %0a%3c the root of it is diminutive. For sciatica, the leaves of it are %0a%3c taken, seven days consecutively, in doses of three oboli, in two %0a%3c cyathi of wine : this is a very bitter potion, however. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 85 . -THE CHAMiELEUCE, FARFARUM, OR FARFUGIUM : ONE %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c The chamaeleuce 40 is known among us as the “ farfarum” or %0a%3c “ farfugium it grows on the banks of rivers, and has a leaf %0a%3c %0a%3c 33 This, Fee says, is consistent with modern experience ; indeed it is %0a%3c drastic to a dangerous extent. 34 “ Albugines.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 35 Or “ ground fig.” The Euphorbia chamaesyce, or annual spurge. %0a%3c %0a%3c 36 The juices are irritating and acrid, and would in reality be highly %0a%3c dangerous to the eyes. %0a%3c %0a%3c 37 Owing to its caustic powers, it really is good for the removal of warts. %0a%3c %0a%3c 38 Or “ground-ivy.” SeeB. xvi. c. 62', and c. 49 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 39 Fee 6ays that this comparison is not strictly correct. %0a%3c %0a%3c 40 The “ground-poplar.” See B. xxvi. c. 19. Identified with the %0a%3c Tussilago farfara of Linnaeus; our colt’s-foot. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 87.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE CLINOPODION - , ETC. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 55 %0a%3c %0a%3c %