biferous plant of the Isle %0a%3c of Candia. _ . . %0a%3c %0a%3c 43 “ Ground-cypress.” Identified with the Euphorbia cyparissias of Lin¬ %0a%3c naeus, the cypress spurge. Taken internally, it is a corrosive poison. %0a%3c %0a%3c 41 Or “ vine-leek.” The Allium ampeloprason of Linnaeus, the great %0a%3c round-headed garlic. It is no longer used in medicine, and all that Pliny %0a%3c states as to its medicinal properties is quite unfounded, Fee says. %0a%3c %0a%3c 45 Fee thinks that Pliny has committed an error here, and that the %0a%3c word “ marrubii ” should be substituted, our “ horehound.” He identifies %0a%3c it with the Stachys Germanica of Linnaeus, or base^ horehound; which %0a%3c is more commonly found in the South of Europe than in Germany. %0a%3c %0a%3c 46 Or “ bed-foot.” The Clinopodium vulgare of Linnaeus, our wild %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 56 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c flint’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXIV. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c bles wild thyme in appearance. The stem of it is tough and %0a%3c ligneous, and it is a palm in height. It grows in stony soils, %0a%3c and the leaves are trained regularly around the stem, 17 which %0a%3c resembles a bed-post in appearance. This plant is taken in %0a%3c drink, for convulsions, ruptures, strangury, and wounds inflicted %0a%3c by serpents: a decoction is also made of it, and the juice is %0a%3c similarly employed. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 88.-THE CLEMATIS CENTUNCULUS ; THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c We shall now have to annex some plants, of a marvellous %0a%3c nature no doubt, but not so well known, reserving those of a %0a%3c higher reputation for the succeeding Hooks. %0a%3c %0a%3c Our people give the name of “ centunculus,” 48 to a creep¬ %0a%3c ing plant that grows in the fields, the leaves of which bear a %0a%3c strong resemblance to the hoods attached to our cloaks. By %0a%3c the Greeks it is known as the “ clematis.” Taken in astrin¬ %0a%3c gent wine it is wonderfully effectual for arresting 41 * diarrhoea: %0a%3c beaten up, in doses of one denarius, in five cyathi of oxymel %0a%3c or of warm water, it arrests haemorrhage, and facilitates the %0a%3c after-birth. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 89 . -THE CLEMATIS ECHITES, OR LAflINE. %0a%3c %0a%3c The Greeks have other varieties also of the clematis, one of %0a%3c which is known as “ echites” 50 or “lagine,” and by some as %0a%3c the “ little scammony.” Its stems are about two feet in height, %0a%3c and covered with leaves: in general appearance it is not %0a%3c unlike scammony, were it not that the leaves are darker and %0a%3c more diminutive; it is found growing in vineyards and cultivated %0a%3c soils. It is eaten as a vegetable, with oil and salt, and acts as %0a%3c a laxative upon the bowels. It is taken 51 also for dysentery, %0a%3c %0a%3c basil. It has some useful properties attributed to it; but what Pliny here %0a%3c states respecting it is erroneous. %0a%3c %0a%3c 47 This seems to be the meaning of “orbiculato foliorum ambitu." %0a%3c %0a%3c *i Turner and C. Bauhin identify it with the Gnaphalium Germanicura %0a%3c of Lamarck, and Sprengel with the Polygonum convolvulus of Linnaeus. %0a%3c If so, I ee says, the synonym here given by Pliny is erroneous; for the %0a%3c Greek clematis, there can be little doubt, is the Clematis cirrhosa of Lin¬ %0a%3c naeus. See the account given of the Gnaphalion in B. xxvii. c. 61. %0a%3c %0a%3c 49 All that Pliny states as to its medicinal properties, Fee says, is %0a%3c %0a%3c •erroneous. ; %0a%3c %0a%3c 50 ^ obabl y the Asclepias nigra of Linnaeus, black swallow-wort %0a%3c %0a%3c 51 The Asclepias nigra has no such medicinal effects as those mentioned %0a%3c by Pliny. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 91.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c TUB UliACONTIUM. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 57 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c with linseed, in astringent wine. The leaves of this plant are %0a%3c applied with polenta for defluxions of the eyes, the part %0a%3c affected being first covered with a pledget of wet linen. Applied %0a%3c to scrofulous sores, they cause them to suppurate, and if some %0a%3c axle-grease is then applied, a perfect cure will be effected. %0a%3c They are applied also to piles, with green oil, and are good %0a%3c for phthisis, in combination with honey. Taken with the %0a%3c food, they increase the milk in nursing women, and, rubbed %0a%3c upon the heads of infants, they promote the rapid growth of %0a%3c the hair. Eaten with vinegar, they act as an aphrodisiac. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 90 . -THE EGYPTIAN CLEMATIS, DAPHNOIDES, OB POLY- %0a%3c %0a%3c GONOIDES : TWO EEMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is another kind also, known as the “ Egyptian” 52 %0a%3c clematis, otherwise as “daphnoides” 83 or “polygonoides:” it has %0a%3c a leaf like that of the laurel, and is long and slender. Taken %0a%3c in vinegar, it is very useful for the stings of serpents, that of %0a%3c the asp in particular. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 91 . ( 16 .) -DIFFEKENT OPINIONS ON THE DEACONTICM. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is Egypt more particularly that produces the clematis %0a%3c known as the “aron,” of which we have already 81 made some %0a%3c mention when speaking of the bulbs. Respecting this plant %0a%3c and the dracontium, there have been considerable differences %0a%3c of opinion. Some writers, indeed, have maintained that they %0a%3c are identical, and Glaucias has made the only distinction %0a%3c between them in reference to the place of their growth, %0a%3c assuming that the dracontium is nothing else than the aron in %0a%3c a wild state. Some persons, again, have called the root “ aron,” %0a%3c and the stem of the plant “ dracontium but if the dracon¬ %0a%3c tium is the same as the one known to us as the “ dracuncu- %0a%3c lus,” 85 it is a different plant altogether; for while the aron has %0a%3c a broad, black, rounded root, and considerably larger,—large %0a%3c enough, indeed, to fill the hand,—the dracunculus has a %0a%3c %0a%3c 52 The Vinca major and Vinca minor of Linnaeus, the greater and smaller %0a%3c periwinkle. Fee is at a loss to know why it should be called “ Egyptian,” %0a%3c as it is a plant of Europe. %0a%3c %0a%3c 53 “ Laurel-shaped ” and “ many-cornered.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 54 In B. xix. c. 30. %0a%3c %0a%3c 45 Fee says that the Dracontion of the Greeks and the Dracunculus of %0a%3c the Latins are identical, being represented in modern Botany by the Arum %0a%3c dracunculus of Linnaeus, the common dragon. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 58 PLINY* 8 NATH UAL HI8TOBY. [Book XXIV. %0a%3c %0a%3c reddish root of a serpentine form, to which, in fact, it owes its %0a%3c name.® 6 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 92 . -THE ARON : THIRTEEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The Greeks themselves, in fact, have established an im¬ %0a%3c mense difference between these two plants, in attributing to %0a%3c the seed of the dracunculus certain hot, pungent properties, %0a%3c and a fetid odour 47 so remarkably powerful as to be productive %0a%3c of abortion, 68 while upon the aron, on the other hand, they %0a%3c have bestowed marvellous encomiums. As an article of food, %0a%3c however, they give the preference to the female plant, the %0a%3c male plant being of a harder nature, and more difficult to cook. %0a%3c It carries off, 69 they say, all vicious humours from the chest, %0a%3c and powdered and taken in the form either of a potion or of %0a%3c an electuary, it acts as a diuretic and emmenagogue. Powdered %0a%3c and taken in oxymel, it is good for the stomach; and we find %0a%3c it stated that it is administered in ewe’s milk for ulcerations %0a%3c of the intestines, and is sometimes cooked on hot ashes and %0a%3c given in oil for a cough. Some persons, again, are in the habit %0a%3c of boiling it in milk and administering the decoction ; and it %0a%3c has been used also in a boiled state as a topical application for %0a%3c defluxions of the eyes, contusions, and affections of the tonsil¬ %0a%3c lary glands. * * * * 60 prescribes it with oil, as an %0a%3c %0a%3c injection for piles, and recommends it as a liniment, with %0a%3c honey, for freckles. %0a%3c %0a%3c Cleophantus has greatly extolled this plant as an antidote for %0a%3c poisons, and for the treatment of pleurisy and peripneumony, %0a%3c prepared the same way as for coughs. The seed too, pounded %0a%3c with olive oil or oil of roses, is used as an injection for pains %0a%3c %0a%3c 56 From “ draco,” a “ dragon ” or “ serpent.” Fee says, that it is not %0a%3c to its roots, but to its spotted stem, resembling the skin of an adder, that %0a%3c it owes its name. %0a%3c %0a%3c 57 i; Vi ms .” Fee says that the Arum dracunculus has a strong, fetid %0a%3c odour, and all parts of it are acrid and caustic, while the Arum colocasia %0a%3c has an agreeable flavour when boiled. %0a%3c %0a%3c 69 This, Fee says, is fabulous. %0a%3c %0a%3c 59 Though no longer used in medicine, the account here given of the %0a%3c properties of the Arum colocasia is in general correct, a few marvellous %0a%3c details excepted. %0a%3c %0a%3c 60 Sillig thinks that there is a lacuna here, and that the name “ Cleo¬ %0a%3c phantus ” should be supplied. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Cbap. 92.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE AEON". %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 59 %0a%3c %0a%3c in the ears. Dieuches prescribes it, mixed in bread 61 with meal, %0a%3c for the cure of coughs, asthma, hardness of breathing, and %0a%3c purulent expectorations. Diodotus recommends it, in combi¬ %0a%3c nation with honey, as an electuary for phthisis and diseases of %0a%3c the lungs, and as a topical application even for fractured bones. %0a%3c Applied to the sexual parts, it facilitates delivery in all kinds %0a%3c of animals; and the juice extracted from the root, in combina¬ %0a%3c tion with Attic honey, disperses films upon the eyes, and %0a%3c diseases of the stomach. A decoction of it with honey is %0a%3c curative of cough ; and the juice is a marvellous remedy for %0a%3c ulcers of every description, whether phagedsenic, carcinomatous, %0a%3c or serpiginous, and for polypus of the nostrils. The leaves, %0a%3c boiled in wine and oil, are good for burns, and, taken with %0a%3c salt and vinegar, are strongly purgative; boiled with honey, %0a%3c they are useful also for sprains, and used either fresh or %0a%3c dried, with salt, for gout in the joints. %0a%3c %0a%3c Hippocrates has prescribed the leaves, either fresh or %0a%3c dried, with honey, as a topical application for abscesses. Two %0a%3c drachmae of the seed or root, in two cyathi of wine, are a %0a%3c sufficient dose to act as an emmenagogue, and a similar quan¬ %0a%3c tity will have the effect of bringing away the after-birth, in %0a%3c cases where it is retarded. 62 Hippocrates used to apply the root %0a%3c also, for the purpose. They say too, that in times of pestilence %0a%3c the employment of aron as an article of food is very beneficial. %0a%3c It dispels the fumes of wine ; and the smoke of it burnt drives %0a%3c away serpents, 63 the asp in particular, or else stupefies them to %0a%3c 6uch a degree as to reduce them to a state of torpor. These %0a%3c reptiles also will fly at the approach of persons whose bodies %0a%3c have been rubbed with a preparation of aron with oil of %0a%3c laurel: hence it is generally thought a good plan to administer %0a%3c it in red wine to persons who have been stung by serpents. %0a%3c Cheese, it is said, keeps remarkably well, wrapped in leaves %0a%3c of thiB plant. %0a%3c %0a%3c 61 F6e thinks that, thus employed, it would be more injurious than %0a%3c beneficial. Though Pliny is treating here of the Arum colocasia or %0a%3c Egyptian Arum, he has mingled some few details with it, relative to the %0a%3c Arum dracunculus, a plant endowed with much more energetic properties. %0a%3c See Note 57 above. %0a%3c %0a%3c 62 See B. viii. c. 54, as to the use alleged to be made by animals of this %0a%3c plant. %0a%3c %0a%3c 63 Fee says that this is very doubtful. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 60 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pltnt’s natural htstort. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXIV. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 93 . -THE DRACTJNCUL0S ; TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The plant whioh I have spoken of 65 as the dracunculus, is %0a%3c taken out of the ground just when the barley is ripening, and %0a%3c at the moon’s increase. It is quite sufficient to ha^e this %0a%3c plant about one, to be safe from all serpents; and it is said, %0a%3c that an infusion of the larger kind taken in drink, is very useful %0a%3c for persons who have been stung by those reptiles : it is stated %0a%3c also that it arrests the catamenia when in excess, due care being %0a%3c taken not to let iron touch it. The juice of it too is very use¬ %0a%3c ful for pains in the ears. %0a%3c %0a%3c As to the plant known to the Greeks by the name of “ dra- %0a%3c contion,” I have 66 had it pointed out to me under three dif¬ %0a%3c ferent forms ; the first 67 having the leaves of the beet, with a %0a%3c certain proportion of stem, and a purple flower, and bearing %0a%3c a strong resemblance to the aron. Other persons, again, have %0a%3c described it as a plant 69 with a long root, embossed to all ap¬ %0a%3c pearance and full of knots, and consisting of three stems in all; %0a%3c the same parties have recommended a decoction of the leaves %0a%3c in vinegar, as curative of stings inflicted by serpents. The %0a%3c third 70 plant that has been pointed out to me has a leaf larger %0a%3c than that of the cornel, and a root resembling that of the reed. %0a%3c This root, I have been assured, has as many knots on it as the %0a%3c plant is years old, the leaves, too, being as many in number. %0a%3c The plant is recommended also for the stings of serpents, %0a%3c administered either in wine or in water. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 94.-THE ARISAKOS : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is a plant also called the “ arisaros,” 71 which grows %0a%3c in Egypt, and is similar to the aron in appearance, only that %0a%3c it is more diminutive, and has smaller leaves; the root too is %0a%3c smaller, though fully as large as a good-s