a%3c ticularly useful for wounds. The people of that country say %0a%3c that, applied with axle-grease, it will knit together and unite %0a%3c the tendons of oxen, when they have been accidentally severed %0a%3c by the plough-share . 74 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 96. -THE PSEUDOBUNION : FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The pseudobunion 75 has the leaves of the turnip, and grows %0a%3c in a shrub-like form, about a palm in height; the most %0a%3c esteemed being that of Crete. Eor gripings of the bowels, stran¬ %0a%3c gury, and pains of the thoracic organs, some five or six sprigs %0a%3c of it are administered in drink. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 97.-THE MYRRHIS, MYRIZA, OR MYRRHA : SEVEN %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The myrrhis , 76 otherwise known as the myriza or myrrha, %0a%3c %0a%3c 72 Or “ ten thousand leaves.” The Myriophyllum spicatum of Linnaeus, %0a%3c according to most authorities, though Fee considers it very doubtful. %0a%3c %0a%3c 73 Possibly the Achillea millefolium of Linnaeus, our milfoil or yarrow. %0a%3c It is still said to have the property of healing wounds made by edge-tools, %0a%3c for which reason it is known in France as the “carpenter’s plant.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 74 This assertion, as Fee remarks, is more than doubtful. %0a%3c %0a%3c 75 “ Bastard turnip.” Desfontaines identifies it with the Bunium aro- %0a%3c maticum; Fee queries whether it may not be the Pimpinella tenuis of %0a%3c Sieber, found in Crete. The Berberis vulgaris has been also suggested. %0a%3c %0a%3c 76 Desfontaines identifies it with the Scandix odorata of Liunseus. Har- %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 02 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXIV. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c bears a strong resemblance to hemlock in the stem, leaves, and %0a%3c blossom, only that it is smaller and more slender : it is by no %0a%3c means unpleasant to the palate. Taken with wine, it acts as %0a%3c an emmenagogue, and facilitates parturition : they say too that %0a%3c in times of pestilence 